# t/research/memory-multiline-description.test — a derived description is ALWAYS one
# physical line (feature-memory.md, Fix 3). A memory whose frontmatter uses a YAML
# literal block scalar (`|`) keeps its interior newlines; unfolded, those newlines
# would break in/MEMORY.md (one line per memory) into stray fragments and shred the
# entry that follows. käsi folds the description to a single line, so the index stays
# a clean list.

send allow-sender { address kasi@decode.ee }

# Seed the multiline-description memory FIRST, then a plain one — model order is the
# index order, so `second-note` is the entry laid immediately after `multiline-desc`.
memory write multiline-desc [fixture memory/multiline-desc.md]
memory write second-note    [fixture memory/second-note.md]

# The reducer derived the block scalar's three lines folded to ONE, joined with
# single spaces (never a naive first-line read, never the raw newlines).
memory multiline-desc description is "First line of the description. Second line that must fold in. Third line."

deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "pay"
    body    "pay the EU invoice attached"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent

# The käsi-authored index carries that whole description on ONE physical line: the
# space-joined form appears verbatim (it can't, if the newlines had leaked through).
task 1 input MEMORY.md matches "*— First line of the description. Second line that must fold in. Third line.*"

# ...and the entry AFTER it is still a proper `- [...]` list item: the multiline
# entry's line ends right at "Third line." and the very next physical line is
# second-note's list item — no fragment wedged between them.
task 1 input MEMORY.md matches {*Third line.
- [second-note](memory/second-note.md) — *}
